{
  "slug": "conclave-crackles-and-christopher-nolans-helicopter-movie-ta",
  "title": "‘Conclave’ Crackles, and Christopher Nolan’s Helicopter Movie Takes Off",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Chris Ryan"
  ],
  "published": "2024-11-01",
  "runtimeMin": 128,
  "format": "Sean and Chris Ryan open on the rumor that Christopher Nolan's next film is a Blue Thunder remake, which spins into Chris's game: VHS-store classics to hand our current auteurs. Then Anna Kendrick's Woman of the Hour, and a long dig into Conclave, the papal-election thriller they both loved and Sean cooled on. Sean closes with documentarian Matt Turnauer on his James Carville film.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Christopher Nolan’s Next Movie",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Blue Thunder",
          "year": 1983,
          "note": "The rumor Chris floated a week earlier and turned out to be right: Nolan's next, with Matt Damon and Tom Holland at Universal for summer 2026, is a take on John Badham's 1983 helicopter-cop movie with Roy Scheider and Daniel Stern. Sean's case for it: Nolan hasn't been in the skies since Dunkirk, and 'let a great director iterate on thin pulpy material' is how the golden age worked. Over/under a billion? Chris says under."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "list",
      "heading": "VHS Classics for Our Auteurs to Remake",
      "note": "Chris Ryan's game: one director per video-store cover",
      "picks": [
        {
          "by": "Ti West",
          "title": "The Hitcher",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "Rutger Hauer and C. Thomas Howell in a serial-killer cat-and-mouse; the VHS cover of eyes in the rearview is basically a West shot. Do it as a period piece or find whatever's left of hitchhiking in 2024."
        },
        {
          "by": "Coralie Fargeat",
          "title": "Little Darlings",
          "year": 1980,
          "note": "Kristy McNichol and Tatum O'Neal racing to lose their virginity: sexy and a little predatory, but weirdly sincere, written by two women. Fresh meat for the director of The Substance and Revenge."
        },
        {
          "by": "Noah Baumbach & Greta Gerwig",
          "title": "The Money Pit",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "The disastrous Tom Hanks / Shelley Long house comedy, part War of the Roses, part acid look at American consumerism. Sean wants to see Baumbach's dark heart and Gerwig's optimism collide on a couple losing all their money. Driver and Johansson to star."
        },
        {
          "by": "Nicolas Winding Refn",
          "title": "Remo Williams: The Adventure Begins",
          "year": 1985,
          "note": "Guy Hamilton's American-spy oddity with Fred Ward; hasn't aged well (Joel Grey plays a Korean man). Give it to Refn and Gosling and stretch it to eight or sixteen episodes."
        },
        {
          "by": "Lee Isaac Chung",
          "title": "Rad",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "Chris's favorite BMX movie ever. Karate Kid meets Breaking Away on freestyle bikes, restored to 4K. His pitch: Chung scales back down from Twisters to a small-town drama about a kid who rides."
        },
        {
          "by": "Denis Villeneuve",
          "title": "The Quiet Earth",
          "year": 1985,
          "note": "Geoff Murphy's New Zealand last-man-alive film with Bruno Lawrence, all sand and empty municipal buildings: 'Dune if everyone died.' Desolation is one of Villeneuve's key themes."
        },
        {
          "by": "Arkasha Stevenson",
          "title": "The Lost Boys",
          "year": 1987,
          "note": "Chris admits this is the one everyone's precious about, but the Santa Cruz boardwalk and teen-vampire clique feel ready-made for the director he's high on after The First Omen."
        },
        {
          "by": "The Safdie brothers",
          "title": "Three O'Clock High",
          "year": 1987,
          "note": "Phil Joanou's high-school riff on High Noon: a movie about stress and time slipping away, so who better than the Safdies. The illustrated cover of the guy hanging off a giant clock is stuck in Chris's head."
        },
        {
          "by": "Sean Baker",
          "title": "The Legend of Billie Jean",
          "year": 1985,
          "note": "Helen Slater and Christian Slater as working-class Corpus Christi kids who become Texas folk heroes, a Bonnie and Clyde with an early viral-fame streak. Maybe too low-stakes for a fresh Oscar winner, unless Billie Jean's a sex worker."
        },
        {
          "by": "Jordan Peele",
          "title": "The People Under the Stairs",
          "year": 1991,
          "note": "The Wes Craven allegory about a Black family and a murderous white couple, a clear precursor to Get Out. Sean doesn't think the original works, but calls the structure pure Peele."
        },
        {
          "by": "Jeremy Saulnier",
          "title": "The Hot Spot",
          "year": 1990,
          "note": "Dennis Hopper's Texas noir with Don Johnson, Virginia Madsen, and Jennifer Connelly, close to pornography in the best way. Flip the genders: Austin Butler comes to town, Sydney Sweeney's the gal. 'Let's print money.'"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Woman of the Hour’",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Woman of the Hour",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Anna Kendrick's directorial debut, which she also stars in: a 70s-LA serial-killer thriller sharded across several potential victims. Based on the true case of a killer who went on The Dating Game. Both liked it: propulsive, savvy about true-crime mania without exploiting it, and with real ideas about the male gaze. Daniel Zovatto is punishing as the killer; Tony Hale plays the smarmy host. Played TIFF 2023, now a Netflix hit."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Conclave’",
      "note": "full spoilers, including the ending",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Conclave",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Edward Berger's papal-election thriller from a Robert Harris novel (screenplay Peter Straughan, score Volker Bertelmann). Ralph Fiennes anchors it as Cardinal Lawrence, the story's detective and moral conscience; Stanley Tucci (Bellini), John Lithgow (Tremblay), Sergio Castellitto (a scene-stealing, vape-hitting Tedesco), and Isabella Rossellini in essentially one good scene. Both were entertained by a pulpy, Agatha Christie-plotted crowd-pleaser dressed as a prestige drama: 12 Angry Men crossed with an airport novel. Carlos Diehz's Benitez wins and is revealed to be intersex; Sean's jaw dropped the first time, then he cooled to the twist on a second viewing, finding it a cheap, Pollyanna-ish shock. A real three-and-a-half-out-of-five, sitting in the Best Picture race mostly on cast and pedigree."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Matt Turnauer on ‘Carville: Winning Is Everything, Stupid’",
      "guest": "Matt Turnauer on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Carville: Winning Is Everything, Stupid",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Turnauer's mostly-verité portrait of James Carville, the self-described hack who sees politics as selling. The film started as a retrospective and transformed when Carville inserted himself into the 2024 race over Biden's fitness. Turnauer talks getting Bill Clinton on camera, and finally landing Mary Matalin for a six-hour, no-tripod porch interview; his through-line of films that wander into a marriage (the Reagans, Scotty Bowers, Roy Cohn); and his theory that documentary has filled the void left by the vanished serious mid-length drama."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
